This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with the problem of fixation prediction, which is a common task in computer vision. Additionally, the paper proposes a principled approach to solve the benchmarking problem, which involves probabilistic modeling and optimization, making it relevant to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of Bayesian decision theory, which is a common technique in the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category. Finally, the paper focuses on saliency maps, which are used to evaluate the performance of models in human-computer interaction (cs.HC) tasks.
